        <ul>
            <li><strong>Sari:</strong> The sari is a timeless and elegant traditional attire for women in India. It is a long piece of fabric, usually six to nine yards in length, that is draped beautifully around the body. The style of draping varies across different regions of India, and it is commonly worn during festivals, weddings, and other special occasions.</li>
            <br/>
            <li><strong>Kurta and Pajama:</strong> The kurta is a loose-fitting tunic worn by both men and women. It is paired with pajama, which is a comfortable drawstring trouser. This attire is prevalent throughout the country and is worn casually as well as semi-formally on various occasions.</li>
            <br/>
            <li><strong>Dhoti:</strong> The dhoti is a traditional garment worn by men. It is a rectangular piece of cloth that is wrapped around the waist and legs, resembling a skirt. The dhoti is commonly worn during religious ceremonies, festivals, and other traditional events.</li>
            <br/>
            <li><strong>Sherwani:</strong> The sherwani is a formal outfit for men, often worn during weddings and special occasions. It is a long coat-like garment with intricate designs and embroidery, paired with churidar or pajama. The sherwani exudes a regal and majestic charm.</li>
            <br/>
            <li><strong>Lehenga Choli:</strong> The lehenga choli is a traditional outfit for women, particularly popular in North India. It consists of a flared skirt (lehenga), a fitted blouse (choli), and a matching dupatta (scarf). The lehenga choli is commonly worn during festivals, weddings, and celebratory events.</li>
            <br/>
            <li><strong>Turban:</strong> The turban is a significant part of traditional dressing for men in India. It is a headgear made of a long piece of cloth wrapped around the head. Different regions have unique styles of turbans, and they hold cultural and religious importance.</li>
        </ul>
